title: For Sale:  Walther P88 9x19
postcontent:
Excellent condition full size Walther P88 9x19mm handgun of early vintage (no channel in slide, tall sights, dovetailed front sight, short trigger bar), before Walther began changing features to reduce cost. Less than 10,000 were made - far less in this configuration. 

The gun features one unified "control lever" that disengages the slide stop with the first operation and decocks the hammer with the second. This control lever is mirrored on BOTH sides of the gun, as is the magazine release and the manual slide stop, making the gun FULLY AMBIDEXTROUS without any modification. It has an adjustable rear sight and an incredibly good DA/SA trigger.

These guns are known for being incredibly accurate and are widely regarded as the best of the "wonder nines." This example has extremely tight barrel-to-slide and slide-to-frame fit. 

I am not the original owner of this handgun. It shows little mechanical wear. There is minor cosmetic wear likely from storage (see pics).

ARMSLIST shrinks photos, the gun can be viewed here:

title: For Sale:  Ruger Red Label 20 Gauge with 300 H&H
postcontent: Up for sale is a very handsome double rifle built on a Ruger Red Label action. The quality of the wood is exceptional, as the pictures show. Said double rifle is a 300 H&H conversion made by the famous gunsmith B. Searcy. (See last photo for Searcy inscription.) The double barrel length is 24 inches. Also included is a Ruger 26-inch 20-gauge O/U barrel set (skeet/skeet), a Leupold 1x4 variable scope and a spare butt stock (also mint), which was taken off simply to replace it with a highly figured stock. (All items shown in the pictures are included.) The entire double rifle and scope weighs 9.8 pounds. (If the successful bidder would prefer to have a 20-gauge shotgun barrel set with factory removable factory chokes, I have a set in excellent condition that will fit for $150 extra.) The condition of all (metal, wood and scope) is nothing less than mint. No cracks, scratches or dings on anything. As is shown in the 10th photo, there are two different ejectors styles on the rifle barrel set. The original Ruger grip caps (both butt stocks)are not present, as the pictures show. Concerning regulation. I have not done a lot or experimentation, but I have reloaded with 180-grain bullets and 65 grains of IMR 4350. At 50 yards, the lower barrel formed 1.5-inch clusters at 11:00 (11 o'clock) and the upper barrel shot 1.5-inch clusters at 5:00. The center-to-center spread was 4.5 inches. Better groupings can undoubtedly be obtained with additional experimentation. (One might even end up shooting different loads in the two barrels to really close the spread.) Most all double rifles require such a trial-and-error process to reach optimum accuracy. Check out the price Searcy is currently charging for double barrel sets. Over two years ago, they were charging in excess of $4000. ALSO, THE SHOTGUN, BY ITSELF, IS WORTH $1000 IN THIS CONDITION. The gun has never been in the field. It has always been stored in a padded case. Wood is above average in terms of figure, but not outstanding, as the photos show.
